</div></section><p id="P24"><a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a> shows results for the association between drug use and any clinical fracture risk after adjustment for propensity score. For anxiolytics and sedatives significant interactions with age and dose were present (p&lt;0.01). In general, the increased in fracture risk from these drugs increased with higher doses of these drugs but declined with age. Although an excess risk was still present in the highest age stratum (&gt;60 years), the detrimental effect of anxiolytics on fracture risk in the highest dose group (≥0.33 DDD/day) was highest in patients aged ≤40 years ( OR 1.76 (1.56-1.98)) and lowest in those aged over 60 years (OR 1.25 (1.21-1.29), p for trend &lt;0.01).</p>
